<TEXT>
a new disposable diaper is designed to keep 
babies dry without chemicals and plastics that take centuries to 
disintegrate in landfills 
the biodegradable diaper introduced at a news conference 
tuesday along with 2yearold twin models buck and elizabeth is 
made of a newly developed plastic 
the material contains a starchfree additive that allows the 
material to be attacked by insects bacteria and enzymes in a 
landfill environment said suzanne sheltonfoley marketing vice 
president of rocky mountain medical corp a small publicly owned 
greenwood colobased company that has been selling a 
chemicalfree diaper for about a year 
the new diaper called the chemicalfree tendercare 
biodegradable takes about two years to biodegrade compared with 
an estimated 200 to 400 years for the typical disposable diaper 
she said 
the company that developed the plastic which ms sheltonfoley 
declined to identify plans to use it in other disposable consumer 
products such as garbage bags she said 
like rocky mountains chemicalfree tendercare diaper the new 
product does not contain chemical polymer salts used by other 
manufacturers in disposable diapers to absorb wetness 
such chemicals can cause eye and respiratory irritation when 
inhaled ms sheltonfoley said though she acknowledged that rocky 
mountains diapers are not as absorbent as those containing such 
chemicals 
dr richard rosenbaum a former pediatrician founder and 
chairman of rocky mountain said many parents are concerned about 
using diapers that contain chemicals although he did not know of 
any evidence that they caused health problems 
dr sidney hurwitz a yale university pediatrician and chairman 
of the american academy of pediatrics dermatology section said in 
a telephone interview that chemicalcontaining diapers pose no 
health threat to babies 
although he said he was not familiar with the new product the 
idea is great provided its safe i think everybody is 
interested in things that are biodegradable 
ms sheltonfoley said tests on babies have shown the product is 
safe 
a canadian company has made biodegradable diapers but rocky 
mountains product is the worlds only chemicalfree 994 percent 
biodegradable diaper she said 
rocky mountain has hired a diapermaker to manufacture the 
product which should be available to consumers by mail or through 
catalogs in december she said 
like the companys chemicalfree diaper the product will cost 
59 for a box of 294 newbornsize diapers about 35 percent higher 
than others on the market ms sheltonfoley said the higher price 
is due to costs associated with mailing and manufacturing 
rosenbaum said he believes parents will be willing to pay more 
for the product 
parents want to know that mother nature can degrade the 
diapers after they are deposited in the county landfill and they 
dont want chemicals added to their infants diapers he said 
