sept 23 
the duluth minn newstribune on the state of education in the 
united states 
do we as a nation have to worry about scientific illiteracy as 
we march into the 21st century 
the us department of education reported last week that 
american young people continue to perform poorly on science 
proficiency both in comparison with their counterparts in other 
nations and in comparison with us school students two decades ago 
the study found that only 7 percent of the nations 17yearolds 
have enough scientific knowledge to do well in college science 
courses and that more than half of americans of that age are so 
illeducated in science that they cannot perform jobs requiring 
technical skills or benefit from special job training 
but perhaps more alarming than that the study found that 
science proficiency for black and hispanic students aged 13 to 17 
is at least four years behind the levels of white students of the 
same ages and that a considerable difference in science exists 
between males and females of that age group 
one thing is clear all is not well with education in america 
