<TEXT>
a group representing the nations hog farmers 
said wednesday it once again will seek import duties on pork 
products from canada claiming that the canadian meat is subsidized 
and competes unfairly with american producers 
ray hankes president of the national pork producers council 
said a petition asking for the countervailing duty on canadian meat 
will be filed with the commerce department and the us 
international trade commission 
the announcment was made at a news conference during a threeday 
legislative meeting of the council in washington hankes said the 
council also would seek financial support from the meatpacking 
industry 
a countervailing duty on canadian hogs was obtained in 1985 a 
move that was upheld by the us court of international trade 
during a lengthy appeals process that import duty remains in 
effect 
but the pork producers also sought to include canadian pork 
products in the 1985 case contending that producers and meat 
packers were part of the same industry and are linked through a 
continuous line of production 
the commerce department ruled in 1985 that subsidies being paid 
to canadian hog farmers justified us duties on imports of pork 
products but the us court of international trade acting on an 
appeal by the canadian meat council overruled the commerce 
decision 
hankes said the council was successful in including an amendment 
in the recent trade law that in effect overturns the earlier 
court decision and reinstates the commerce departments authority 
to impose duties on processed pork to the full extent of subsidy 
payments made to canadian hog producers 
in 1985 the pork council predicted that if a countervailing 
duty was imposed on canadian hogs but not on pork products the 
canadians would simply slaughter more hogs and send the products 
into the united states 
that in fact has occurred the council said in 1984 
imports of pork products from canada equaled 345 million pounds by 
the end of the current year estimpated pork product imports to the 
us from canada will total 526 million pounds thats a 52 percent 
increase since the councils original petition was filed 
further the council said imports of subsidized pork are 
capturing a growing percentage of the us market and seriously 
depressing us hog prices 
the council cited a study by university of missouri economist 
glenn grimes showing that imports of pork products from canada 
depressed us hog prices as much as 381 per hundredweight 
during the first six months of this year 
council officials added that means us pork producers 
suffered a potential revenue loss of as much as 393 million in the 
first half of 1988 as a result of subsidized canadian pork imports 
gross revenue losses to us meat packers are even higher 
the council said it does not seek to inhibit free trade and 
competition between canada and the united states but does want 
to ensure that all producers and packers domestic and foreign 
operate under the same market conditions undistorted by government 
financial intervention 
</TEXT>
