<DOCNO> AP880928-0175 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
private economists reacted with skepticism 
wednesday to george bushs proposal for new taxdeferred savings 
accounts for the middle class 
democrat michael dukakis was already using the proposal as 
ammunition for his contention that a bush presidency would favor 
the rich however republican bush defended his plan to set up 
individual savings accounts saying they would give taxpayers 
a little nest egg 
many private economists called the tax savings inconsequential 
and said it was unlikely such accounts would be used by very many 
americans 
the vice presidents proposal which he first described on 
tuesday would allow people to deposit up to 1000 annually in a 
special savings account and defer taxes on the interest if the 
money was kept in the account for a minimum of five years 
while the interest would accumulate tax free during that time 
it would be taxed at the savers regular tax rate once it was 
withdrawn 
that would mean that the only benefit to the taxpayer would come 
from additional interest earned on money that would otherwise be 
taxed immediately 
the amount of the benefit would depend on whether the taxpayer 
was being taxed at a 15 percent or 28 percent rate and how much his 
investment was earning 
michael boskin a stanford economist and a top bush economic 
adviser said that a taxpayer being taxed at a 28 percent top rate 
who put 1000 into the special savings accounts every year for 10 
years would accumulate about 500 in tax savings at the end of 10 
years this assumes that the investments earned 10 percent annually 
boskin called the plan a modest additional proposal and said 
it should be viewed as complementing other savings incentives such 
as existing individual retirement accounts and bushs proposal for 
college savings bonds in which the income from the bonds would be 
tax free if it went to college tuition 
but other economists said the modest benefits the bush campaign 
was claiming would be even less when the savings were invested for 
a shorter period of time or at lower interest rates 
this is an attempt to help the middle and lower economic 
classes save more money but it is small potatoes and it is 
questionable as to whether it will produce much of anything at 
all said allen sinai chief economist of the boston co 
the economists all said that boosting americans low savings 
rates was a worthy goal since that would free more money for 
investment in areas to boost the countrys productivity but they 
said this plan was unlikely to have much effect they said a much 
better approach would be to cut the federal budget deficits which 
would also free money for investment 
we have implemented a slew of savings incentives in the past 
several years and yet personal savings rates remain at record 
lows said lawrence chimerine president of the wefa group an 
economic consulting firm in bala cynwyd pa one reason people 
arent saving more is that they feel they cant because their 
living standards are already being squeezed 
several economists noted that dukakis had already seized on the 
disparity between bushs plan for middle class savers and the vice 
presidents proposal to cut the capital gains tax rate from the 
current 33 percent maximum down to 15 percent dukakis said the 
capital gains cut would mean an average 30000 windfall for the 
wealthiest 1 percent of americans 
george bush plays santa claus to the wealthy and ebenezer 
scrooge to the rest of us dukakis said wednesday as he waved a 
20 bill which he said represented the amount the average family 
would save with the bush accounts 
robert reischauer an economist at the brookings institution who 
advises dukakis said that someone with a moderate income taxed at 
a 15 percent rate putting 1000 in the bush account per year 
would realize total tax savings of 944 for each 1000 invested 
that saving would go to 1477 per 1000 for someone taxed at a 
28 percent tax rate reischauer assumes the investments would earn 
8 percent interest per year 
david wyss an economist at data resources inc a lexington 
mass economic consulting firm called the tax savings trivial 
i think he needed to come up with some kind of tax break for 
the middle class to balance the freebies he wants to give the rich 
with the lower capital gains tax wyss said 
but john makin an economist with the conservative american 
enterprise institute said that the bush proposal would be more 
attractive for people willing to leave their investments alone for 
longer periods 
its better than nothing but its not going to change the 
world dramatically makin said and its going to look a lot 
less attractive if you are talking five years of contributions 
and a 15 percent tax bracket 
</TEXT>
