<TEXT>
the united states has reached a historic 
agreement to import chinese breeding swine in hopes of upgrading 
american pork supplies the agriculture department said wednesday 
deputy secretary peter c myers said the contract involves 
usdas agricultural service chinas ministry of agriculture and 
the chinese national animal breeding stock import and export corp 
the imports will include 144 pigs of the meishan ming and 
fengjing breeds he said the animals will be used in research 
studies under a cooperative agreement with the usdas meat animal 
research laboratory at clay center neb the university of 
illinois and iowa state university 
myers a hog farmer from missouri said he talked about the 
potential agreement during his june 1987 visit to china he said 
china has about 100 breeds of swine that represent a unique 
reservoir of unexplored germplasm that could offer potential 
benefits for the us industry 
this unexploited source could prove to be very valuable to 
the us research programs on resistance to diseases parasites and 
improvement of some production traits he said china has a 
long history in the domestication of pigs that can be traced back 
for at least 6000 years 
according to usda reports china also is the worlds largest hog 
producer at the end of 1983 for example china had an inventory 
of 2985 million hogs compared with 558 million for the united 
states at that time 
a department spokeswoman sandy miller hays said she did not 
know and could not find out immediately how much the pigs cost the 
united states or whether there might be other terms involved 
a goal of the import program is to cross the chinese breeds with 
us breeds to increase litter size while maintaining the quality 
and lean yield of pork the breeds being imported have three to 
four more pigs per litter than the average us breed 
the animals will be imported in late march 1989 after spending 
60 days in quarantine in china and meeting other health 
requirements they will be quarantined again for 120 days at usdas 
animal import center in fleming key fla before being released 
for research 
roger j gerrits of the departments agricultural research 
service said scientists hope to conduct at least five years of 
research to evaluate the animals and determine if they should be 
released for use by the us swine industry 
gerrits said that us swine geneticists recognized the 
potential value of chinese swine more than 10 years ago but 
satisfactory health and quarantine requirements were not 
completed until last year 
the three breeds selected for the research studies are highly 
prolific he said us geneticists estimate it would take at 
least 30 generations of conventional selection to increase the 
litter size of the average us swine breed to the level routinely 
produced by these chinese breeds 
each university and the usda agency will conduct its own 
research program but projects at each will be coordinated gerrits 
said provisions also have been made for the exchange and sharing of 
germplasm semen and other genetic material in case of a disease 
outbreak or other unexpected losses 
</TEXT>
