<TEXT>
research into the growing and use of kenaf a 
fibrous plant that can be used to make paper is getting more 
attention after a decade on the back burner the agriculture 
department said wednesday 
howard e waterworth coordinator of kenaf research for usdas 
agricultural research service said 300000 is being invested this 
year in kenaf studies through agency laboratories in lane okla 
and weslaco texas another 300000 is scheduled for 1989 
industry trials including test runs by several us 
newspapers indicate that pulp from kenaf makes newsprint paper 
that is as sturdy as woodpulp paper but generally is brighter 
consumes less ink and has less ink ruboff waterworth said 
kenaf can be grown in southern us areas such as texas 
florida georgia mississippi and california he said the plants 
grow 15 to 18 feet in height in less than five months and can grow 
to around 22 feet an acre yields 7 to 10 tons of dry fiber 
the peoria ill journalstar in 1977 was the first newspaper 
to make a press run on kenaf newsprint at least eight other 
newspapers have had similar tests including the most recent in 
july 1987 at the bakerfield californian 
agency research on kenaf was suspended in 1978 when supplies of 
paper pulp were plentiful and prices were down waterworth said 
the usda has spent about 900000 to support commercial 
development of kenaf through private industry since 1986 and the 
new funds for research are expected to give additional support 
to that enterprise he said 
