<TEXT>
the presidents chief economic adviser said 
wednesday that slowing economic growth in the second half of the 
year should ease inflationary pressures and help bring down 
interest rates 
beryl sprinkel chairman of the presidents council of economic 
advisers said he expected overall economic growth would drop below 
3 percent in the second half of 1988 
the economy as measured by the gross national product grew at 
an annual rate of 32 percent in the first six months of the year 
sprinkel said growth could slow to 28 percent in the final six 
months and still be enough to meet the administrations target of 3 
percent growth for all of 1988 when measured from the fourth 
quarter of 1987 
sprinkel said the slower growth should help ease fears that the 
country was about to embark on a renewed inflationary spiral 
triggered by heavy demand bumping up against tight labor markets 
and high factory operating rates 
this slowdown should help lower interest rates sprinkel said 
my own view is that we can expect some relief on interest 
rates in the period ahead he said 
sprinkel said the slowdown has caused the unemployment rate to 
rise slightly in the past two months although it still remained 
near 14year lows in august the jobless rate was 56 percent up 
from 53 percent in june 
sprinkel predicted the downward trend should resume helping to 
push the jobless rate toward 5 percent 
sprinkels comments came in a briefing to reporters on the 
70month expansion since the 198182 recession a recovery which 
sprinkel credited to the progrowth economic policies pursued by 
president reagan 
the present recordbreaking expansion has raised living 
standards reduced poverty reduced inflation and created nearly 18 
million new jobs most of them good jobs at good rates of pay 
sprinkel said 
