<TEXT>
president reagan on tuesday signed an 88 
billion military construction spending bill but gave agreed only 
partially to a requirement that the administration notify 
congressional committees in advance of some military exercises 
the legislation requires 30 days notice from the secretary of 
defense to specified committees of the plans and scope for any 
proposed military exercise involving us personnel if construction 
costs are expected to exceed 100000 
the president said he was approving the bill with the 
understanding that this section encompasses only exercises where 
providing 30 days advance notice is feasible and consistent with 
my constitutional authority and duty to protect the national 
security 
the compromise measure adds to the current fiscal year 
construction budget of 83 billion but falls short of the 97 
billion sought by reagan 
the measure includes 65 million for the final stage of 
construction of a national test facility in colorado for reagans 
strategic defense initiative also known as star wars the 100 
million project will be used to test sdi components 
reagan had also sought 31 million for construction of a 
railroadbased version of the mx nucleartipped missile but 
congress appropriated no funds for the purpose leaving the 
decision on the future of the railbased mx weapon up to the next 
administration 
the measure provides 173 million to the navy to build new bases 
around the nations coasts and 50 million to build a closed 
incinerator at tooele army depot in utah to destroy obsolete and 
aging chemical weapons the army is continuing work on new chemical 
weapons although the president has called for an international 
conference to outlaw their use 
the measure was the sixth bill the president has signed out of 
the 11 appropraitions measures that congress considers each year 
