use of spanish bases 
the deal was sealed at a meeting between secretary of state 
george p shultz and spanish foreign minister francisco 
fernandezordonez 
for the first time state department spokesman charles e redman 
said no us economic or military aid will be provided for use of 
the bases 
redman said the agreement underscored that a us military 
presence in spain served the common interest of the two 
countries 
he also said the two sides were able to resolve a nuclear 
question that had become entwined in the negotiations 
spanish prime minister felipe gonzales initially had vowed to 
keep spanish territory and naval ports free of us nuclear 
weapons worldwide us policy meanwhile is to neither confirm 
nor deny the presence of such weapons on american warships or 
fighter planes 
