<TEXT>
nearly a year after the crash of 1987 wall 
street is still retrenching and recuperating 
the growth that doubled the number of jobs in the securities 
industry from 1979 to mid1987 has given way to layoffs mergers 
and costcutting 
stock prices have staged a modest rally this year recovering 
some of the huge losses they suffered in the slide that culminated 
in a record 226 percent drop for the dow jones industrial average 
on black monday oct 19 
but the mood and tempo of the marketplace still bear little 
resemblance to the bull market that prevailed for five years before 
the collapse 
in a business that thrives on activity buying and selling that 
generates commissions and trading profits volume has lagged all 
year even shortterm plays like stockindex arbitrage and 
maneuvers to capture dividends have lately died down 
if those gimmick transactions and trades between dealers most 
of which dont bring the street much revenue are excluded john 
connolly an analyst at dean witter reynolds inc estimates that 
volume is down 30 percent or more from a year ago 
business is contracting he said mutual fund sales have 
stagnated pension fund managers are struggling with meager cash 
inflows and lots of plan terminations 
some steps have been taken and others proposed to strengthen 
the mechanism of the marketplace which was sorely taxed in the 
worst moments of the crash 
for example the national association of securities dealers the 
organization that operates and regulates the overthecounter 
market has adopted new systems and rules to keep 
computertocomputer trading going when the pressure on the market 
intensifies 
the new york stock exchange and the chicago mercantile exchange 
have come up with plans for circuit breakers designed to 
prevent breakdowns in runaway markets 
many observers see measures like these as single pieces in a 
larger puzzle still unsolved by the financial community 
the no 1 issue is to restore investor confidence said 
william schreyer chairman of merrill lynch amp co 
the crash clearly left a lasting imprint on individual investors 
the socalled retail customers who were already a diminishing 
breed 
an opinion research corp survey conducted for the nasd in may 
and june found that 39 percent of the respondents had grown more 
conservative in their investment strategies 
more than 60 percent described the stock market as riskier for 
individual investors than it was a year earlier 
the crash brought a sudden halt to more than a decade of rapid 
growth for the discount brokerage business which caters especially 
to affluent knowledgeable individual investors and which depends 
heavily on commissions from that clientele 
in the first quarter of 1988 according to the securities 
industry association wall streets main trade group retail 
commissions fell 27 percent from the comparable period a year 
earlier 
if individual investors were frightened by the crash why didnt 
they cut back drastically on their spending causing a slump in the 
consumer economy 
the answer seems to be that as a group they hadnt plunged 
heavily into the market before the crash 
at merrill lynch one of the biggest fullservice firms 
catering to the public schreyer said only 25 percent of customers 
money was in stocks going into the debacle 
assets in those accounts stood at about 250 billion on sept 30 
of last year he said a month later they had fallen to 238 
billion but they since have rebounded to about 260 billion 
far more important than individuals as a driving force in the 
stock market are money managers at investing institutions who 
handle pension funds and other large pools of assets 
while investing in stocks or bonds may be optional for an 
individual professional portfolio managers operate in a different 
environment they are paid to put money to work within a relatively 
limited range of choices 
but since the crash money managers also have been content to 
sit with largerthanusual cash reserves parked in shortterm 
interestbearing investments such as treasury bills 
thanks in part to inflation worries and recent credit tightening 
by the federal reserve these lowrisk securities now offer yields 
of 75 to 8 percent or more 
in strong stock markets most money managers fear nothing more 
than underperformance failing to keep pace with their 
competitors and the rise of the market averages if it goes on for 
very long underperformance is a sure road to losing accounts and 
maybe your job as well 
in the 198287 bull market many observers say the performance 
race helped keep the advance going far beyond any level that made 
rational sense 
in todays cautious environment the pressure to perform while 
still present is far less intense in many a strategy meeting 
these days the talk focuses on limiting risk 
by the logic that makes the market work declines in stock 
prices end and new bull markets are born when worries are rampant 
cash reserves are high and everybody has gotten out of stocks in 
that gloomy setting there is nobody left to sell 
some wall streeters argue that the market is now at or nearing 
such a point but others arent so sure 
its too late to be really bearish and too early to become 
bullish said raymond f devoe jr an analyst at the firm of 
legg mason wood walker inc 
there will occur at some stage a major turning point said 
anthony tabell at delafield harvey tabell inc in princeton nj 
it will be accompanied by maximum pessimism and consequent large 
holdings of cash 
however there is nothing to stop the current climate of 
skepticism from continuing for a protracted period it is difficult 
to tell therefore when and where that turning point will be 
in the meantime optimists in the financial world tide 
themselves over with the thought or at least the hope that most 
of the damage from the crash has been confined to wall street 
perhaps it was just an extreme manifestation of the markets 
continuous upanddown cycle the end of an era for wall street 
but not the end of the line for prosperity in the industrialized 
world 
it always repeats itself said schreyer a market recovery 
awaits he contends and i think its going to be sooner rather 
than later 
i dont think this malaise is going to last for years 
not everybody shares that optimism the nearterm outlook 
isnt likely to improve substantially until full investor 
confidence is restored in both the integrity of the marketplace and 
the strength of the economy edward obrien president of the 
sia said in a generally bleak crash anniversary appraisal 
in the regulatory arena there have been a few steps taken to 
curtail some of the practices and problems which occurred a year 
ago but major regulatory reform hasnt taken place 
</TEXT>
