<TEXT>
black monday the 500 billion crash heard 
round the world left no craters on main street 
in the first hours and days afterward there were stories of 
people pawning watches and buying gold real estate markets ground 
to a halt and some highfashion clothiers in manhattan 
contemplated fire sales on suspenders 
but one year later such doomsday scenarios have given way to 
more hopeful appraisals 
while the crash instilled caution in the hearts and minds of 
investors cut the value of many stock portfolios and eliminated 
thousands of jobs on wall street other damage has been limited 
across america 
the figures say the nations wealth shrank by the equivalent of 
2000 for every us citizen on oct 19 but the reality was less 
severe in most places 
it was kind of a nonevent as far as we were concerned said 
doug fairweather director of corporate media relations for sears 
roebuck amp co the nations largest retailer 
even in new york the epicenter of the market crash officials 
say the impact on state finances was negligible 
new york is experiencing a revenue shortfall during the 
current fiscal year but really that is a result of changes from 
the federal income tax not related to the stock market said 
ann doyle spokeswoman for the state budget division 
charitable giving did not decline although the rate of increase 
in 1987 was 665 percent compared to an increase of 9 percent the 
year before said david tobin of the national center for charitable 
statistics 
home buying and retail sales slowed in many part of the country 
but other factors rising interest rates and indifference to 
fashion trends for instance were to blame for the sluggishness 
the shock of the stock market crash was mostly absorbed because 
the loss really didnt amount to 2000 per person after all most 
stock is in the hands of the upper crust not average americans 
there was an initial shock but the other shoe never dropped 
for consumers or any of the others of us said sandra shaber of 
the futures group an economic forecasting firm in washington 
thats not to deny that there was a real crash her firm 
estimated that household net worth home equity and financial 
instruments such as stocks and bonds fell at an annual rate of 
222 percent in the last quarter of 1987 
