the third worlds 12 trillion debt should be 
reduced but only in ways that private markets find acceptable 
us treasury secretary nicholas f brady has told world financial 
leaders 
brady also ruled out strategies that would turn over risky loans 
from private banks to creditor banks governments and their 
taxpayers and touted the use of debtequity swaps and other 
innovative devices for reducing debt 
if we embark on a course that involves the transfer of risk 
from the private to the public sector a true and lasting solution 
to the restoration of sustained growth among debtor nations will 
have escaped he said 
brady making his first appearance on an international stage as 
treasury secretary spoke at tuesdays opening formal session of 
the annual meeting of the world bank and the international monetary 
fund the meeting continues through thursday 
most of the ministers of finance from the 151 member government 
are attending the meeting along with thousands of representatives 
of banking and industry 
brady left for washington right after his speech giving no 
public indication whether or not he was criticizing a japanese 
debtrelief proposal that would allow some latin american debt to 
be converted into bonds with lengthened repayment terms 
brady defended the socalled baker plan which calls for 
providing new loans to developing countries that enact economic 
liberalization policies the plan was devised by his successor 
former treasury secretary james a baker iii 
the united states regards with skepticism proposals that may 
appear to conform to the basic principles of the debt strategy but 
which in practice will produce only an illusion of progress 
brady said indeed such proposals will make the debt problem 
intractable 
without singling out any idea brady said such measures could 
weaken international institutions and prompt political opposition 
in creditor countries 
the japanese proposal outlined by satoshi sumita governor of 
