<TEXT>
sources at international coffee organization talks 
said a us proposal tuesday on regulating supplies and prices 
would tend to benefit latin american producers at the expense of 
most african countries 
they said the effect of the us proposals for the coming year 
would be to transfer export market share from producers of the 
cheaper robusta grade to those selling the soughtafter arabica 
type 
the sources at the london talks spoke on condition of anonymity 
the bulk of robusta production about 25 percent of all world 
coffee grown from africa principally the ivory coast uganda 
cameroon zaire and madagascar the biggest producer outside the 
region is indonesia 
arabicas are grown throughout latin america with brazil and 
colombia the biggest producers kenya ethiopia tanzania and india 
are the only significant nonlatin american producers 
under the us proposal on the shape of the icos market control 
plan for the year beginning oct 1 producers would be exempt from 
reductions in export quota if the price of their type of coffee 
exceeded 125 a pound 
the average price of arabicas is just over 130 on world 
markets and robustas averaged slightly more than 90 cents 
the us plan calls for an initial 198889 global export quota 
of 58 million bags which would be cut by 15 million bags if the 
ico indicator of the average price of robustas and arabicas was 
115 or below any time during the year one bag equals 60 kilos 
or 132 pounds 
a further cut of 15 million bags would take place not less than 
10 days after the first if the indicator remained below 115 a 
pound 
the indicator currently just above 113 is likely to be 
below 115 on oct 1 thereby triggering an immediate reduction in 
the 198889 global quota industry sources said 
current prices levels are telling us that the brunt of that 
cut would be borne by robustas if the united states has its way 
said a trader 
the price of this grade was certain to be below 125 and that 
of arabicas just as certain to be above he said 
robusta producers would also risk losing out under the us 
proposal if any quota increases took place in 198889 the sources 
said 
earlier tuesday officials of brazil and colombia the worlds 
two biggest coffee producers said they were ready to open 
negotiations with consumers on a pricesupport regime following 
agreement on a joint position 
the braziliancolombian proposal calls for an initial global 
export quota of 54 million bags for 198889 the aim would be to 
defend an unchanged price range in the area of 120 to 140 a 
pound 
the 198788 ico export quota stands at 515 million bags 
according to a copy of the braziliancolombian proposal the 
198889 global quota would be increased at fixed trigger prices to 
reach 58 million bags balance between supply and demand at 
130 a pound 
it would let producers of arabica coffee have a greater share of 
any quota increase than those growing the cheaper robusta grade 
all proposals presented tuesday will be considered by a special 
contact group of key ico countries set up to try to negotiate a 
pricesupport deal for 198889 by the scheduled end of the talks on 
sept 30 
the united states the european economic community and other ico 
consumers want to increase supplies of mild arabicas in 198889 
because of growing demand for this grade and the record premium its 
price has established over robustas 
