<TEXT>
it was sunny and mild in downtown manhattan the 
morning of monday oct 19 1987 but black storm clouds had 
gathered inside the balconied trading room of the new york stock 
exchange 
at 930 am the opening bell clanged and the storm broke 
in the next 6 hours a halftrillion dollars of stock wealth 
disappeared and the dow jones average of 30 industrial stocks lost 
a recordshattering 508 points 
stock prices had fallen fitfully since late august when the dow 
jones average peaked at 272242 
the friday before black monday the average posted its first 
tripledigit decline 108 points culminating the biggest weekly 
decline since world war ii 
over the weekend investors asked themselves whether the 
fiveyear bull market had ended interest rates were climbing the 
trade deficit seemed intractable and us officials were wrestling 
with west germans over economic policy 
before trading opened stocks fell sharply in tokyo and london 
and a huge reservoir of sell orders piled up awaiting execution in 
new york the dollar plunged and gold soared to its highest level 
in almost five years 
adding to the pessimism a bulletin said the united states had 
destroyed an iranian oil platform in the persian gulf 
prices on the nyse plunged from the opening bell the dow jones 
average fell about 69 points by 10 am and an unprecedented 201 
points by 11 am 
then there was a bounce a breath of hope for the market by 
noon the average was down just 128 but then the selling resumed 
with just two modest rallies around 1 pm and 230 pm 
the most blindly relentless sellers were portfolio insurers 
whose strategy called for them to sell clients stocks or 
stockindex futures whenever the market went down 
the volume of more than 600 million shares overwhelmed the 
computerized trading system and damaged a crucial link between the 
nyse and the futures markets in chicago 
small investors were last in line to sell some brokers took 
their phones off the hook 
rumors spread shortly after 1 pm that the nyse would be 
closed and a rapid denial by the securities and exchange 
commission failed to convince nervous traders 
the bond market had fallen most of the day but began a powerful 
rally in late afternoon traders decided the crash signaled a 
recession or worse which would be good for bond prices 
shortly before 3 pm the dow jones average had lost roughly 250 
points from then on stocks went into a sickening free fall that 
was terminated only by the closing bell at 4 pm 
at 545 pm federal reserve chairman alan greenspan stepped 
off a plane in dallas and asked someone how the market closed 
down fiveoheight the official said 
for a moment greenspan was relieved thinking the person meant 
508 points instead of 508 for greenspan as for the rest of the 
world black monday took a moment to sink in 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

