<TEXT>
the federal energy regulatory commission today 
sent the proposed merger between pacificorp and utah power amp light 
co back to its staff for further information 
the ferc staff presented the commission with a draft that would 
have permitted the merger but required the combined company to 
auction its excess transmission capacity the utility would then 
have to construct additional transmission capacity when it was 
needed 
the merger between the companies based in portland ore and 
salt lake city would create an 8 billion utility serving 12 
million customers in seven western states 
under the proposal owners of utah powers common shares would 
receive pacificorp stock worth between 3225 and 38 a share 
depending on its average closing price over the 10 days after the 
merger was approved the utility has 596 million shares of common 
stock outstanding 
commissioners asked the ferc staff to justify imposing any 
conditions on the merger and to submit a more detailed 
recommendation next week they then will vote on it individually 
without another formal meeting 
the two utilities say their merger would save them 500 million 
the first five years and that utah powers rates would drop between 
5 percent and 10 percent the proposal would make utah power a 
division of pacificorp along with the latters electricity 
business pacific power amp light co 
the merger has been approved by shareholders of both companies 
and regulators in all the states that would be affected 
a federal administrative law judge recommended ferc deny the 
combination however saying the merger would be anticompetitive 
and that the utilities had failed to show it was in the best 
interest of the public ferc staff lawyers later recommended the 
merger be approved subject to certain conditions 
pacificorp chairman don c frisbee has said his utility would 
not pursue the merger if ferc rejected it 
the proposed merger was approved by regulatory commissions in 
oregon utah washington california idaho wyoming and montana 
because utah powers electricity needs peak in the summer 
airconditioning months and pacific powers are highest during the 
winter heating season the merger would give the combined utility 
as long as a decade before it would have to build new electricity 
plants officials of the two companies have said 
the increased consumption during the winter also would boost 
utahs coal mine production utah power spokesman dave mead said 
earlier this month utah financier ian cummings chairman of the 
new yorkbased holding company leucadia national corp made a 12 
billion cash bid for a majority interest in the privately held 
utility or about 600 million less that pacificorps 
utah power officials refused to comment but wall street 
analysts were baffled why leucadia would be interested in the 
regulated utility saying they did not anticipate any significant 
earnings growth over the next few years as a standalone company 
an oregon utility watchdog organization has sued the state 
public utility commission in an effort to block the merger the 
citizens utility board claims in the lawsuit oregon ratepayers 
would subsidize utah powers ratepayers because the latter would 
receive a rate reduction 
spokesmen for the state agency and pacificorp said safeguards 
are built into the proposal that would prevent oregon ratepayers 
from subsidizing those in utah 
</TEXT>
