a federal court judge on wednesday 
dismissed a motion that would have given a group of dissident 
shareholders leverage to depose zenith electronic corps board of 
directors 
us district judge joseph j farnan dismissed the challenge 
from brookhurst partners because he said federal court did not have 
jurisdiction over the subject matter 
brookhurst spokesman tom franco said the group would sue zenith 
in delaware state court which we believe to be the correct 
forum 
brookhurst is seeking shareholder support to dump seven of 
zeniths 10 directors trim the board to six members and fill three 
of those seats with nominees committed to selling the television 
and computer maker 
brookhurst had asked the court to strike down a company bylaw 
that requires approval from all shareholders not just a majority 
for such a move 
zenith which is incorporated in delaware but based in glenview 
ill unilaterally agreed monday to such a change but franco said 
the companys action was not enough and brookhurst still was 
seeking access to the companys shareholder lists and financial 
records 
there are other claims and we believe that they remain worthy 
of the courts consideration franco said in a telephone 
interview wednesday night were hopeful that there will be a 
prompt resolution of the remaining claims 
franco said the group would file a motion thursday in delaware 
chancery court seeking to exempt brookhursts solicitation from 
zeniths poison pill takeover defense 
the plan now gives zenith the right to dilute its holdings if 
any one shareholder gains consent for change from 15 percent of the 
shares 
brookhurst is a limited partnership that owns 61 percent of 
zenith stock which makes the group the companys largest 
stockholder 
